column168: Compartment #2 of tanker #50 was being loaded at the Quality Terminal in Chester, SC on June 2, 2009 with Isopropy Acetate.  Compartment 1 was loaded with no issues.  When compartment #2 was loading, our Driver noticed material leaking from the valve.  The driver stooped loading after about 200 gallons was put into the compartment.  He noticed that there were a 2 bolts missing from the inner valve on compartment #2.  Our Driver along with a couple of employees from the Quality Terminal were able to tighten the rest of the bolts and install the 2 bolts that were missing.  About 50 gallons drained into the site spill control area.  After the bolts were installed and the rest were secure, there was no leakage.  The remaining 150 gallosn was put back into the rail car.  The tanker had just been in our local repair shop, Truck Services of Virginia for repair of the inner valve.  The tanker was picked up on Monday as completed.  In short, the shop did not tighten up the bolts as they should have and they must have vibrated lose on the trip to SC.  Once we got the truck back to Virginia, compartment 1 was of loaded, tanker purged and it was sent back to the shop for reapir.  We picked up the tanker on June 5th along with a report that said all bolts were replaced and tighten to current spec.
column169: When I returned to the office on June 5th and was told of the incident, I called Truck Services of Virginia and expressed my concerns.  They hav agreeed to give a written summary of all repairs from here on out.  In addition, I have told my drivers to inspect any repairs that are done by this vendor and our other vendor, to the best of thier ability before leaving the shop.

column168: While being switch at the KCS Kansas City, Missouri railroad classification yard, the UTLX 641162 was discovered leaking from the top area of the tank car.  This tank car was immediately isolated from the yard to prevent further movement action created release and to facilitate safe emergency response.  Emergency response contractor Hazmat Response, Inc, of Olathe, Kansas, was mobilize and found the vacuum relief valve housing missing the internal operating components (plug stem, spring, washer and nut).  Field investigation concluded that the nut which retained the plug-stem to the spring and washer was not wrench tight and vibrated off enroute thus causing the release in the Kansas City yard. Photographs of the failed device are attached. The defective vacuum relief valve was replaced with a new valve. The shipper is now arranging for field pressure test or FRA movement approval to progress tank car to destination.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.

column168: BNSF operating personnel reported ACFX 87680 (DOT 111A60W1 tank car) in the railyard dripping product down its side shell. ACFX 87680 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with a receptacle placed under it to catch any fall-off product droplets. BNSF contract responders were dispatched on 6/08/09 to inspect ACFX 87680 and eliminate leak sources. Responders reported all valves were found closed and secure. The manway cover bolts were all tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected and this examination revealed abrasions on the gasket surface and some cracking around the gasket rim. Responders concluded that the manway gasket wasn't sealing properly and a new manway gasket was applied. The manway cover was then closed and properly secured. The spillage on the side shell of ACFX 87680 was cleaned. Response was concluded by 1415 hrs. CDT, 6/08/09.  The side specification stencil on ACFX 87680 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2006 and next due in 2016.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On June 2, 2009 at 23:14 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Woodbourne yard discovered TILX 110092, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper PPG Canada (Chemtrec #2009060200251), and local agencies were notified. React, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a blown non reclosing safety vent (rupture disk). Contractor personnel replaced the disk with like in kind and decontaminated the car from the spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code:441  NARRI:  2 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40

On 06/04/09 at 10:05 hrs., personnel in the Wauhatchie yard in Chattanooga, TN, discovered two rail cars, PROX 24031 and GATX 18048, had derailed on the switch lead. The switchman on scene observed a liquid coming from the bottom of PROX 24031, a loaded tank car of Styrene Monomer Stabilized. The fire department was contacted and ordered a  mile evacuation. This included 2 warehouses next to the rail yard employing approximately 100. At 12:16 hrs., the fire department lifted the evacuation after discovering the liquid coming from the bottom of the rail car was condensation that was trapped between the tank car shell and tank car jacket. Both rail cars were re railed and sent to the car shop for repairs, before forwarding to destination. There was no release of hazardous material, this report filed account of the evacuation ordered by the local Fire Department.

While delivering fuel via a nozzle, the nozzle became dislodged. Approx. 75-100 gallons sprayed on top of the delivery tank truck. Kitty littler was spread over spill to help isolate the spill. Soil was excavated to remove all contaminated soil. Samples were taken to verify  all contaminated soil was removed. New soil was imported and old soil was taken to treatment facility under haz waste manifest.
column169: All drivers have been re-trained on reporting and spill response guidlines. all truck delivery procedure have been reviewed.

column168: An eastbound BNSF train that just departed Alliance, NE was reported with a possible leaking entrained tank car. This train stopped at Ellsworth, NE to setout the suspected railcar TILX 150442 (AAR 211A100W1 tank car) for further inspection by a BNSF hazardous material responder. The responder reported a small amount of dried/hardened residue product on the side shell of TILX 150442. It could not be readily determined when this spillage was deposited. A detailed inspection revealed the only securement issue found on TILX 150442 is that its 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured. After the responder scraped the hardened product residue from around pressure relief device housing, the frangible disc was replaced in kind.

column168: A FACILITY EMPLOYEE NOTICED THE CONTAINER SMOKING/SMOLDERING INSIDE THE REAR OF THE TRAILER THAT WAS PARKED AT VEOLIA'S 10-DAY IN TRANSIT FACILITY LOCATED IN PHILADELPHIA, PA. THE EMPLOYEE USED THE FORKLIFT TO REMOVE THE PALLET FROM THE TRAILER TO ISOLATE THE MATERIAL FROM THE OTHER WASTE PRESENT AT THE FACILITY. THE TRAINED FACILITY EMPLOYEES DONNED THE APPROPRIATE PPE AND REMOVED THE SMOLDERING PACKAGE AND OTHER AFFECTED PACKAGES FROM THE PALLET. THE SMOLDERED PACKAGE HAD BROKEN 1/5 BOTTLES OF NITRIC ACID (OTHER THAN RED FUMING)INSIDE THE LAB PACK CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER AND OTHER AFFECTED CONTAINERS THAT WERE NEXT TO THIS PACKAGE ON THE PALLET, WERE REPACKED ACCRDING TO DOT REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES TO EMPLOYEES AND THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF MATERIAL (NITRIC ACID LIQUID)TO THE SURRONDING AREA (CONCRETE DOCK) THE NITRIC ACID WAS ABSORBED BY THE VERMICULITE MATERIAL WHICH WAS INSIDE THE LAB PACK CONTAINER USED TO SUPPORT/CUSHION THE BOTTLES DURING TRANSPORTATION.
column169: THE SIZE OF THE CONTAINER USED AS THE OUTER PACKING DID NOT ALLOW ENOUGH SPACE BETWEEN THE INNER BOTTLES. THE BOTTLES RUBED/STRUCK AGAINST EACHOTHER DURING TRANSPORTATION CAUSING 1 OF THE BOTTLES TO BREAK. THE VERMICULITE SETTLED ALSO DURING TRANSPORTATION WHICH ALLOWED THE GLASS BOTTLES TO BANG.RUB AGAINST ONE ANOTHER WHICH CAUSED THE BREAKING OF 1 BOTTLE. A SAFETY ALERT WILL BE SENT OUT TO ALL EMPLOYEES OF THE INCIDENT AND REVIEW OF LAB PACKING PROCEDURES WILL BE REVIEWED FOR ALL EMPLOYEES.

column168: CGTX 26253 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) at the repair track for wheel assembly work was reported emanating a residue product odor. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected CGTX 26253. The responder reported finding the valve stem packing retainer nuts on the liquid valve and the vapor valve loose with both of these valves in the closed position. These retainer nuts were tightened which eliminated any further product odor. There was no indication of any liquid product release. CGTX 26253's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2002 and next due in 2012. The intact seals on the valve housing cover, the liquid valve and the vapor valve were replaced by BNSF seals.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported UTLX 201851 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) sloshing product from the manway closure during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and no further product release was observed. UTLX 201851 was then carefully moved and cordoned off in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection by hazardous material responders. BNSF contract responders were dispatched to inspect UTLX 201851 and eliminate any further product release from UTLX 201851. Responders reported that all seals were intact and a slight product staining at the base of the manway nozzle was observed. Inspection of the manway closure revealed that all manway securement bolts were tool tight. Inspection of the manway gasket revealed no visual defects of the gasket. The responders replaced the manway gasket with a new Teflon gasket to ensure a good seal. The manway cover was closed and properly secured. Afterwards, UTLX 201851 was moved back and forth to test the manway closure seal and no product leaks were observed. All previous spillage atop the tank shell had evaporated. New security seals were applied and response was concluded by 1820 hrs. CDT, 6/08/09.

column168: The UPRR was notified by a concerned citizen that a BNSF train parked in the siding at UPRR station Fauna was venting from an entrained tank car. A BNSF mechanical-hazardous material responder was dispatched to investigate. Also, BNSF contract responders were dispatched to assist. The responders reported entrained GATX 61247 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) was found with all four bolt nuts on the liquid line assembly blind flange were less than tool tight. This condition allowed product to vent at the flange with the vent mist settling atop this tank car near the valve housing area. The responders' tool tightened the loose flange bolt nuts by 0940 hrs. CDT, 6/09/09. The small amount of product accumulation around the valve housing area was neutralized with a solution of soda ash and water. Afterwards, this neutralized mixture was wiped. No evidence of ground impact was observed. Response was concluded by 1020 hrs. CDT, 6/09/09.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully inplemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

The collapsed outer metal cage cut into the inner receptacle and liquid product sloshed out from the damaged area during transit. The responders transferred the remaining product within the damaged IBC into six 55 gallon steel drums and loaded these drums back into the cleaned FSTZ 820891. The empty damaged IBC was removed by the responders for future appropriate disposal.

Driver uses tractor mounted pump and 80 feet of 2" product hose to make delivery into tots. driver has assistance from plant operator who operated loading devise for filling tots. When the tote is full the operator signals to driver to shut down pump before the operator can shut his valve. on the filling of the first tote, the operator signald to driver to shut down pump the driver was not ready and failed to disingage the PTO for the pump. the operator closed his valve, pressure continued to build in the hoses, the coupling end on one of the hose failed and parted from the hose resulting in the spill. spilled material was contained and within 45 minutes was cleaned up and a replacement hose was placed in service. Delivery was completed without incident.
column169: 1) The driver needed to remain in the cab of the tractor to disengage the PTO to stop the pump. The driver gave the operator permission to start but failed to position himself properly to respond to the operator's command. 2) The internal by-pass on this pump might have pervented the release if it were operational. This was determined after the incident when the pump was cleamed and sent out for inspection.  3) The hose in question is also being inspected and may have been damaged prior to use.  Driver faces disciplinary action per company policy pending completion of our investigation.

The shipment was found by a FedEx Courier who had handled the last undeclared shipment from this shipper. The box was returned to the FedEx station where it was opened. We found five bottles of perfume. There were no markings, labeling,shipping papers, emergency response information or other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. I notified the FAA, I spoke to SA Deborah Kennedy. I finally found a phone number to discuss the two shipments of perfume.The shipper was allegedly unaware that perfume was regulated. In advised her employees needed to be trained and that emergency response was required. The shipper advised that would not ship any more perfume.

THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED FIBERBOARD BOX SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE BROKEN OPEN DURING OFFLOAD OF THE INBOUND TRUCK. THE PACKAGE WAS VERY HEAVY AND THE PACKAGE WAS NOTICED TO HAVE SEVERAL SMALL CYLINDERS OF CARBON DIOXIDE, WHICH ARE USED IN PAINT BALL GUNS. THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED GAMES AND TAPES. INOTIFIED SEAN MAHONEY OF THE CMH/FAA ON 6-11-2009 AT 15:25 (CDT) TO NOTIFY HIM OFTHE SHIPMENT. I SENT HIM A NOTIFICATION OF UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHEET, THE AIRBILL, & PACKAGE SCANS. I ALSO SENT IT TO HODGE MORTON OF THE CLE/FAA. I ASKED THE CLE RAMP PERSONNEL TO PROVIDE SOME DOCUMENTS REGARDING THE INCIDENT, AS THE ORIGINAL FIBERBOARD BOX THIS WAS SHIPPED IN, WAS ACCIDENTILY DISPOSED OF BEFORE THEFAA CAME TO VIEW. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED, AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT.ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO SEND THE NON HAZARDOUS ITEMS ON TO THE CONSIGNEE AFTERTHE FAA HAD VIEWED, AND THE CONSIGNEE WAS TO DRIVE TO THE CLE RAMP TO PICK UP THE PAINT BALL CYLINDERS.

column168: We were loading the waste drums to be transferred to the disposal site.  The carrier signed for the load and as they were leaving the yard. The driver heard a noise and felt the trailer shake.  The carrier opened the doors to the trailer and noticed that one of the 55 gallon drums over preasurized and popped split open the drum at the top seam and sprayed materail on the side wall and ceiling of the trailer as well as over some other drums that were in close proximate.   The carrier immediately contacted Kevin Homer.  Once Kevin did a quick initial assessment he had the carrier pull back into the dock so that we could better access the situation at hand.   After the carrier backed back into the dock.  We identified the drum that split open at the top  and was able to get the profile and decided to call in an outside clean up crew. The 3 - 5 gallons of material was contained in the trailer nothing leaked out.

UTLX 68858 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shippe representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and found the manway cover gasket missing.  A gasket was installed and the manway cover properly secured stopping the release.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: A shipment of hazardous waste contained within intermediate bulk packages were being received at a transportation related transfer facility for the purposes of being consolidated into a second vehicle for continued transportation.  Upon inspection of the load, it was discovered that 4 of the containers showed evidence of external staining that signified an inner container either broke of opened in transit puncturing the inner liner and soaking into the fiberboard container wall.  Facility personnel immediately halted transfer operation and initated a clean-up operation.  A field Service crew was assembled to repackage the individual containers into appropriate non-bulk packages for continued transportation.  In addition, the contaminated intermediate bulk packages were dismantled and sent for disposal at a licensed waste management facility along with all clean-up debris.
column169: The cause of the incident was attributed to incorrect package preparation.  The choice of an intermediate bulk package for inner containers was performed in error as the material should have been packaged in an appropriate non bulk package.  In additon, sufficient cushioning/absorbent was not used allowing the liquid to soak into the containers material of construction. In order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper of the material was contacted and advised of the situation and instructed that combination packages must be restricted to appropriate non bulk packages.  In addition, the driver that accepted this shipment has been likewise re-educated on container inspection prior to acceptance for transportation.

column168: TILX 303008 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, SPSI, Inc., responded and found vapor leakage at the "A" end liquid line plug and from the pressure plate.  The vapor line plug was removed, cleaned, re-taped and properly installed tool tight.      The pressure plate bolts were tightened with an impact wrench stopping the release.

HOKX 111018 was noted by FRA Hazmat Inspector dripping product from the bottom outlet valve at a rate of about 1 drop per minute.  The car was isolated and the shipper notified.    Shipper representatives responded and replaced the bottom outlet auxilliary valve and plug stopping the release.

On the morning of 6-22-09, the Operations Department was conducting propylene railcar loading operations on railcar TILX 302170.  Propylene loading volume measurement is accomplished by flowing propylene through a metering tube that utilizes the Coriolis effect to provide accurate volume measurements.  The meter tube output is supervised by a computer that provides information to the loading operator.  Additionally, loading volumes are verified by the position of an indicator rod on the propylene railcar.  This rod provides the relative amount of unloaded volume remaining in the railcar.    As the railcar loading was nearing completion, operations personnel noted that the indicator rod changed position from approximately 30 inches to almost 0 inches within a few minutes.  Loading activities on TILX 302170 were stopped immediately and operations personnel retrieved information from the supervisory computer to determine the loaded volume.  The supervisory computer indicated that the railcar had been loaded with approximately 100,057 pound of propylene compared to a fully loaded volume of approximately 120,000 pounds.      The behavior of the railcar indicator rod coupled with conflicting supervisory computer level output resulted in a decision that the railcar quantity needed verification by weighing on the facility complex railcar scales.  The railcar was disconnected from the loading platform and was moved along the rail to the scales within the facility complex.  The railcar scale output indicated that the car was overweight.  Instructions were provided to return the railcar to the loading platform for offloading.    Ambient temperature conditions were extremely high, approaching 100 degrees F with abundant sunshine.    A facility employee observed a small amount of gaseous material escape from the dome area of the loaded railcar.  Williams’ representatives responded to the tank car location.  EPA Method 21 testing verified that the relief valve had re-seated.    Near midday on 6-23-09 TILX 302170 arrived at the loading platform to be positioned for offloading.  At this time, ambient temperature levels were near 100 degrees F.  At approximately 1 P.M. as operations was making connections to offload, the railcar relief valve briefly actuated again.    Connections were completed and railcar offloading began.  No further releases occurred.
column169: Two action items are underway.  1)  The propylene meter tube performance is being closely monitored and will be replaced if warranted.   2)  The railcar was offloaded and will be transported to Trinity Rail for examination and maintenance.    Operations followed safe and appropriate procedures by immediately shutting off flow to the railcar when the level indicator rod abruptly changed position.  Williams will review this event with Operations personnel.

column168: We received a cargo shipment (3 boxes) of "spare boat parts" on June 12, 2009 at MEX. It processed and forwarded by air to PHX. The final destination of the shipment was FLL. When the aircraft arrived in FLL at approximately 17:40 on June 13, 2009, the forward baggage compartment was opened and the cargo agent detected the smell of fuel. The source of the smell was determined to be one of the three boxes that appeared to be fuel soaked. FLL personnel stated that there was no actual leakage from the box.The aircraft was reloaded and dispatched as flight 181 FLL-PHX. After the aircraft departed, FLL personnel notified the OCC and explained that flumes were detected when the ramp agent opened the baggage compartment, OCC made the decision to divert the flight to IAH for safety reasons.We are still in the process of collection information, by it appears that the spare boat parts were not professionally cleaned and purged of residual fuel before they were shipped. This shipment was screened via X-ray and the shipper signed off on the air waybill stating it contained no hazardous materials. The shipment is being held at the FLL cargo facility. It is scheduled to be inspected by Julie Abbott (FAA) on June 16, 2009.

column168: The packages were loaded for local delivery and improperly blocked and braced. U/A to the customer the skid was lying on the side. The shipment was refused and returned to the carrier's facility. The cartons were damp and the release was contained in the carton. Further investigation revealed the carton had no physical visible damage. The lids on 2 of the inner bottles were found to be cross-threaded. The combination of the freight falling over and the cross-threaded lids caused the release of product from the lids of 2 of the inner containers. The release was minimal (6oz.)and contained to the packages. The shipper (Arkema) has provided new cartons to the carrier. The carrier resealed the lids and will repackage the inner containers into the new cartons provided by the shipper and either return to the customer or consignee, which ever the shipper advises. The product released from the lids of the container. The release was managed in approx. 15 minutes and the repackaging will take approx. 60 minutes. No further actions are necessary at this time.

column168: On June 16th at 15:44 hours, FRA Inspector David Snyder, was performing an inspection at the CSXT Southover Yard Facility and discovered UTLX205806, a residue tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., releasing vapors from the pressure relief device valve.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Brabham Oil Company was notified via Chemtrec (report number 2009-0616-00188).  SWS First Response, a CSXT emergency  response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the pressure relief device valve stem broken.  Brabham Oil and Hawkeye Renewables contacted Union Tank Car to respond and replace the defective valve.  Hawkeye Renewables applied for an FRA Movement Approval and the request was granted (FRA-09060263) to send this car to a qualified repair facilty.  Approximately one pound of vapors was released into the atmosphere.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report will be required for this incident.  Note: This incident did require a special shipping move to the car repair shop track.    Cause Code:  418  NARRI: 2(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 28

column168: Petroleum Transport Driver was filling an underground storage tank with gasoline.  The product flow into the tank slowed and then stopped.  The driver, closed the internal valve on tanker unit, waited approximatly 12 minutes for product to drain from the drop hose.  The driver then removed the drop fitting from the UST and as a result of back pressure in the UST product flowed out of the fill pipe on the UST onto the ground.  Product flowed into a storm drain and over to a second strom drain on the property.  Clean-up and containment efforts were begun by the driver.  Then an HM Response contractor arrived and cleaned the product out of the storm drains and flused entire area and vacummed up the product.  The cause of the pressure in the UST is because of a failure of the vapor line ball float vent valve. At the end of the valve is a 3" ball float that was lodged in the vapor tube.  The ball float did not descend from the vapor line allowing the vapor to leave the UST and go back to the tanker, this caused the build up of pressure in the UST.
column169: First the defective Ball Float Vent Valve was replaced in the UST.  Second, the driver has received additional guiadance in regard to not removing the drop fitting from the UST until the pressure issue is resolved and in a similar situation he is required to call his immediate supervisor before proceeding.

column168: Unloading lines were attached and pressure tested to 80 psi. All connections were leak checked and none were found. Pressure was bled off and valves were then opened to start unloading railcar. At about 30 psi on the car, the operator noticed wisps of "smoke." Unloading began approximately 10:00hrs. The smoke was noticed at about 10:15hrs. Unloading was then shut down. The operator then verified that the leak was from under the relief valve. It was decided to finish unloading the railcar at 30psi. The smoke quit about half way through. It started smoking again for about the last 15 minutes. Total unloading time was about 2 hours. Total volume of sulfur trioxide released is estimated to be approximately one (1) teaspoon, per our opacity subject matter expert. There were no off-site consequences and in-plant emergency associated with this release.

column168: On June 26, 2009 A PTC driver was delivering gas into under ground storage when it overfilled. The driver failed to report the spill as required by company policy. column168: A less than truckload quantity of non bulk containers of hazardous waste was being conslidated onto a single van trailer for continued transportation.  During the loading process,a 55 gallon non bulk package was punctured by a small section of a steel support unit of the trailer wall allowing approximately 10 gallons of material to escape onto the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel activated the emergency response plan and initiated the clean-up activities after donning appropriate personal protective equipment.  The response crew secured the damaged container into a suitable salvage drum and used an absorbent material to absorb and collect all material release to the floor of the van trailer.  This material was placed into the salvage drum along with all addition spill debris and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: In response to this incident, the loading personnel were retrained to ensure that before any loading activities commence that they conduct a thorough inspection of the cargo compartment of the van trailer.  The purpose of this inspection is to identify any foreign objects that could damage or puncture the lading. An thorough inspection would have prevented this incident.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc driver was delivering fuel and while unloading the driver noticed product leaking from the overfill sump. The driver immediately shut off the flow of product but approximately 20 gallons had leaked. At the time of spill, Clayton County police were on scene and notified the fire department who then responded to the scene. SWS First Response was brought out to the scene and flushed and cleaned the storm drain. QuikTrip takes full responsibility for the spill as it was later determined that a cap on the sump pipe had not been properly secured. The tanks should have held 9000 gallons and the driver had dropped approximately 5700 when the leak occured.
column169: QuikTrip corrected the problem immediately while our management was on site in effort to not delay any future loads. The driver followed proper unloading procedures.

In route to the refinery where the product was being delivered the driver notice the pressure on his cargo tank was 240 psi. The working pressure on the cargo tank was 265 psi. The driver proceeded to his destination.  Just before arriving at his destination the releif valve releaved the pressure on the cargo tank.  The driver was awear of the release of the product and was in the middle of traffic and a heavy populated area.  He continued to a safe area before pulling over which was about a mile from his destination. By the time he stopped the truck the releif valve had releaved the pressure and reseated. This is what the releif valve is designed to do.  The tempature outside was 100 degree. We thank the releif valve may have releaved a bit early. The product was off loaded at the plant and cargo tank was taken to the main shop to have the releif valve changed out and tested.  The releif valve releaved pressure for about 5 minutes.  We think about 300 gallons was released in vapors.
column169: The cargo tank is being tested and the releif valve is being replaced to prevent this incident from occuring again.

THP narrative: vehicle 1 traveling west on Wolverine road; right side wheels of vehicle 1 exited the north roadway edge; vehicle 1 traveled approximately 110’ along ditch; driver of vehicle 1 steered to the left in an attempt to regain control of vehicle and over corrected. The tractor of vehicle 1 reentered the westbound lane of roadway and traveled approximately 84’; vehicle 1 then overturned traveling 138’ to the final rest; final rest of vehicle 1 was located partially on the roadway. Tractor was on its left side in the westbound lane and the tanker trailer was on its left side along the roadway shoulder. Tanker was leaking heavily through top port.     Driver inattention; failed to maintain proper lane; cited – failure to exercise due care.
column169: Wolverine road is a narrow state highway which is scheduled to be widened to accommodate truck traffic from ethanol plant; power poles had already been moved for road construction.     Driver inattention; failed to maintain proper lane; cited – failure to exercise due care

column168: ON THIS DAY I, CARLTON BARNES, WAS INFORMED THAT THIS PACKAGE WAS UNDECLARED.  IT WAS GIVEN TO ME BY TRACY MAURO TO BE PROCESSED IN THE (DMP).  THERE ARE NO HAZARD PAPERS ON THE BOX; THE BOX WAS COLD TO THE TOUCH.  RICHARD TROIANO DISCOVERED THE PACKAGE ON THE AIR TRAILER.  HE THEN GAVE THE BOX TO TINA ROSANNA WHERE SHE PROCEEDED TO CALL THE HELP DESK.  SHE THEN FOLLOWED THEIR INSTRUCTION TO OPEN THE BOX TO SEE WHAT IN IT.
BOX OPENED ON SIDE AND BOTTLE FELL OUT THAT WAS A OXYGEN COMPRESSED USP.
OXYGEN BOTTLE IN BOX AND WAS HlSSINGS.  WE CLOSED VALVE.

PACKAGE CAME DOWN FROM RETURN 1.  INNER PACKAGING ALREADY OUT OF THE ORIGINAL BOX WHEN SORTER DISCOVERED PACKAGE.  SORTER MOVED PACKAGE TO SORT BELT.  PT SUPERVISOR THEN MOVED PACKAGE TO A NON-FUNCTIONING SORT BELT.  PT SUP CALLED RESPONDER AFTER READING OUTSIDE OF PACKAGE.  RESPONDER RESPONDED TO PACKAGE WITH FULL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT ON, UNTIL RESPONDER FLIPPED PACKAGE AND DISCOVERED A PROHIBITED DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL ON THE PACKAGE.  RESPONDER FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND CONTACTED CONSOLE AND RMP.  THEN RMP AND RESPONDER DECIDED TO EVACUATE SORT 1.  RMP FOLLOWED CHAIN OF COMMAND AND CONTACTED FULLTIME SUPERVISOR, SORT MANAGER, DIST. ENVIRONMENT COORDINATOR, AND PE.  OUTSIDE RESPONDER RESPONDED TO PACKAGE AND DISPOSED OF PACKAGE PLUS ALL OF RESPONDER'S PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT.

RESPONDED TO WING B POSI 5 DUE TO CONDENSATION AND FROST ON THE BOTTOM OF PACKAGE.  UPON INSPECTION DISCOVERED UNDECLARED DRY ICE.  APPROX 2.5 LBS DISCOVERED.  OUTER CARTON WET DUE TO THE NATURE OF DRY ICE.  PROCESSED TO FAA WITH PHOTOS.

column168: BNSF mechanical personnel reported UTLX 500150 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the manway area during normal movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and UTLX 500150 was isolated in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical responder inspected the manway securement and found all manway cover securement bolts/nuts in a tool tight condition, therefore a manway gasket seal problem was suspected. The nearby consignee was notified and assistance requested to inspect the integrity of the manway gasket. Meanwhile, the spillage on UTLX 500150's side shell and safety appliances was wiped and no ground impact was evident. The consignee responder confirmed that the manway seal was intact and all manway securement bolts/nuts were tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected and found with surface cracks over the entire body of the gasket with some of these severe to a shredded like condition. A new manway gasket was installed and the manway cover was properly resecured. Spillage that wasn't cleaned previously was wiped. Response was concluded by 1415 hrs. PDT, 7/01/09.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was enroute from the shippers location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor's 10 day in-transit storage facility pending continued transportation.  WHile at this location, it was discovered tha a small amount of mateial had leaked from the trailer onto the truck parking area.  Facility personnel immediately activated the emergency reposne plan and dispatched a crew to the scene.  Upon arrival, the crew donned appropriate personal protective equipemnt and entered the trsailer.  Once inside, the crew identified a 55 gallon container that had what appeard to be a puncture in the bottom of the container.  The contatiner was placed into a salvage drum and a clay absorbent material was used to absorb all free liquids.  this material was placed into the salvage drum along with all other materials colelcted in response to this release including the material used to decontaminate the trailer floor.
column169: An inspection of the container indicated that a foreign object punctured the bottom of the container dusiring transportation.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the individuals responsible for loading this vehicle have been re-instructed to ensure that prior to placeing a container in the vehicle that the floor must be swept to remove any objects that could adversely affect the condition of the container during transportation.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF outbound train inspection in the railyard revealed entrained UTLX 41132 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with product leaking down its side shell and evaporating in the 100 degree F ambient temperature. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were notified and immediately inspected UTLX 41132. The responders observed the leak source emanating from under the sealed (intact seal ULINE 9588439) valve housing cover. Responders reported finding the threaded liquid and vapor valves hand tight. Internal pressure was relieved and both valves were removed for thread cleaning. After the threaded portion of the valves were cleaned, new Teflon tape was applied to the threaded area. The valves were reinserted into their respective orifices and properly tool tightened. BNSF seal numbered 06157291 was applied to the valve housing cover. Response was concluded by 1255 hrs. PDT, 6/30/09. All spillage rapidly evaporated and no ground impact was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A cargo tank was dispatched to a customers location to accept for transportation a shipment of used oil.  During the loading process, the oeprator initiated the process to switch to the second compartment of the cargo tank and inadvertanly overfilled the first compartment allowing approximatley 3 gallons of oil to escape from the top dome cover onto the side of the trailer and concrete parking area.  The loading ooeration was immedialtly halted and the released oil was cleaned up using the cacuum hose of the tank trailer.  In addition, the side of the trailer was cleaned with absorbent pads and speedi dry.  ALl clean -up debris was containerized and scheudled for disposal at a fully licensec waste management faciltiy.  Prior to departing the laoding site, sufficient material was transferred from the first compartment into the second to ensure sufficient outage was left in the tank before securing the top dome hatch for transportation.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been re  trained on the steps necessary to ensure he is aware and has visbility to the tank level while loading his tank.

column168: Shipment, Conway Pro 733837694 was shrink wrapped and in good condition upon initial check during the unloading process. Conway Driver Ed Bailey drove into the trailer and grabbed the pallet from underneath the load rack, backed away from the rack and raised the pallet up for inspection and noticed a puddle of blue ink in the spot where the pallet had been. Upon further inspection of the pallet, he first looked underneath the pallet to see if there was any fork damage which there was not. He then noticed that the ink was leaking from a drum that was on top of the pallet, sitting directly beside the top of a 55 gallon drum. The 5 gallon pail was pushed into the 55 gallon drum by excessive and very tight shrink wrap, most likely a machine wrap. The pail was dented in direct correlation with the top of the 55 gallon drum, with a tear in the pail approximately 1" long and 1/8" wide, where the ink leaked out.The ink spilled out along the sides of the inner pails on the pallet onto the trailer floor. Approximately 3-4 gallons leaked from the pail. The ink was partly dry and partly wet which makes me believe this started leaking shortly after leaving the origin terminal. (Transit time 24 hours)
column169: Future shipments in which a small and large pails get loaded together should either have some cardboard or other protective material in between the pails, or to make sure that when the drums are shrink wrapped , that there is monitoring as to how tight the wrap gets wrapped to the pallet, when a machine is doing the wrapping.

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON GARMIN MILL ROAD IN MIDLAND, NC AT APPROXIMATELY 7:10 AM ON JUNE 12TH, 2009.  THE DRIVER INDICATED THAT A WASP FLEW INTO THE CAB OF HIS TRUCK CAUSIMG HIM TO LOSE CONTROL OF HIS UNIT.  THE TRACTOR WENT OFF ONTO THE SOFT SHOULDER AND WAS PULLED DOWN THE EMBANKMENT.  IN THE PROCESS OF ROLLING OVER, THE DOME LIDS ON THE TOP OF THE TRAILER WERE DAMAGED.  THIS ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 2600 GALLONS OF ETHANOL TO BE RELEASED.  VARIOUS FIRE DEPARTMENTS IN THE AREA RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  IN ADDITION, KENAN CONTACTED CCI ENVIRONMENTAL AND HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE AND HANDLE THE REMEDIATION.  A SMALL AREA NEEDED TO BE EXCAVATED AND THE CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS EXPECTED.

THE PETROLEUM TANKER (TRACTOR AND SEMI-TRAILER), LOADED WITH GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL, PROCEEDED FROM THE EASTBOUND 91 FREEWAY ONTO THE TRANSITION RAMP TO THE NORTH BOUND 710 FREEWAY.  AFTER ENTERING THE TRANSITION RAMP CURVE, THE TANKER DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE.  THE TANKER HIT THE RIGHT SIDE RAMP BARRIER AND CAME BACK INTO THE TRAFFIC LANES, WHERE IT FLIPPED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE AND SLID DOWN THE RAMP.  THE SEMI-TRAILER CARGO TANK RUPTURED AND CAUGHT FIRE.     FLAMING GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL RAN INTO AT LEAST TWO STORM SEWER PIPES THAT WENT TO A COMMON WATER PUMPING STATION, WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED. THERE WAS NO COMTAMINATION OF ANY STREAM.                                                      THE TRUCK DRIVER WAS NOT ABLE TO GET OUT OF THE TRUCK AND WAS A FATALITY.  IT IS NOT KNOWN AT THIS TIME WHETHER HE WAS KILLED BY THE CRUSH OR THE ENSUING FIRE.  POSITIVE IDENTIFICATION IS YET TO BE COMPLETED BY THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY CORONOR'S OFFICE.                THE ROADWAY AND STORM DRAINS WERE DAMAGED BY THE FIRE.A PORTION OF THE TRANSITION RAMP ROADWAY HAD TO BE REPLACED, AND THE TRANSITION RAMP WAS NOT REOPENED UNTIL THURSDAY, 06/18/2009.  THE TRANSITION RAMP GOES UNDER A COUPLE OF FREEWAY BRIDGES, AND THOSE BRIDGES ARE BEING EVALUATED FOR DAMAGE.HOWEVER, FREEWAY TRAFFIC WAS ALLOWED OVER BOTH BRIDGES SHORTLY AFTER THE FIRE IS EXTINGUISHED AND THE BRIDGES WENT THROUGH A PRELIMINARY EXAMINATION.  THE CONTAMINATED WATER IN THE STORM DRAINS AND WATER PUMPING STATION WAS PUMPED OUT FOR RECYCLING.  STORM DRAINS WERE CLEANED.
column169: Truck drivers operating tanker trucks with a higher center of gravity, and subject to slosh, have to be made aware that curves (especially ramp curves) cannot be taken at the speeds as shown on the road-side signs which appear prior to entering the curve.  They have to understand that these speeds, shown on the signs, are for automobiles and a vehicle with a higher center of gravity must utilize a slower speed.

THE ADVANTAGE TANK LINES DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PUMP DIESEL OUT OF THE CUSTOMER'S UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK ONTO THE TANK TRAILER.  IN THE PROCESS OF DOING SO, HE OVERFILLED THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS SPILLED ONTO THE ASPHALT/CONCRETE PARKING SURFACE.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND ASSISTED THE DRIVER WITH THE CLEAN-UP.  NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS EXPECTED.

Environmental Waste Minimization, Inc. (EWMI) lab pack chemist and driver (Erik Brown) arrived at Delta Circuits (shipper/offerer) in Fairfield NJ to receive and transport a tote of Corrosive Waste Liquid (Sodium Hydroxide) UN3266. Delta Circuits personnel pumped the material from a poly open top tank into the 275 gallon tote (1BC 31HA1). The original scope of work understood by EWMI was to bring a container to allow Delta Circuits to take material out of an on site tank for shipment off site. Delta Circuits personnel wanted to add more material to the tote but this was not authorized by EWMI personnel. Delta Circuits continued to add a drum of the same waste material to the tote and then added 20 to 30 gallons of a copper sulfate <80% and formaldehyde <15% mixture premix solution (1120A Premix, Fidelity Chemical Products Corp.) to the tote. Delta personnel emptied the entire contents from the 55 gallon container of 1 120A Premix into the tote, closed the package and then loaded the tote onto the truck. The tote was secured down by EWMI lab pack chemist Erik Brown. Approximately 30 minutes latter while traveling on Interstate 80 west Erik heard a load bang and promptly pulled over to discover a liquid seeping from the truck. Upon inspection Erik discovered the tote had ruptured at the surface and caused a rip in the tote approximately 2V2 feet in length. An estimated ten gallons leaked out from the tote. The spill was immediately contained with supplies from the vehicles emergency spill kit. The spill was called in and a spill response team was dispatched to the scene. The tote ruptured at the one side on top of the tote. The elapsed time from the moment the driver heard the bang to the time that the rupture was noted and addressed was approximately a minute.

On June 30, 2009 at 14:14 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Queensgate yard in Cincinnati, OH  discovered UTLX 662072, a loaded tank car of Turpentine, emitting vapors from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified.  Eagle Construction, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found there was a nick or small cut in the manway gasket. column168: CAP ON BOTTLE WAS CRACKED, DUE TO BEING DROPPED, CAUSING LIQUID TO LEAK.

PACKAGE WAS COMING DOWN BELT WHEN A PICKOFF NOTICED A WET CORNER AND IMMEDIATELY CALLED FOR THE BELT TO BE STOPPED. ALSO NOTIFIED A SUPERVISOR.  ANOTHER RESPONDER AND I QUICKLY IDENTIFIED THE PACKAGE CONTENTS BASED ON OUTER MARKINGS.  WE USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL ON THE BELT, THEN MOVED PACKAGE DOWN TO THE HAZMAT CENTER FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  CAP WAS LOOSE ON BOTTLE ALLOWING LIQUID TO LEAK.

DONNED PPE AND TOOK SPILL CART TO PINK BELT FOR HAZARD LEAKER.  USED DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET TO CHECK FOR HAZARDS, USED UNIVERSAL ABSORBENT TO CLEAN UP SPILL. BOX DROPPED DAMAGING 2 OF THE INNER RECEPTACLES' CAPS CAUSING THE LEAKAGE.

PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED FROM TRAILER.  UNLOADER REQUESTED A HAZMAT RESPONDER TO CHECK PACKAGE TO MAKE SURE IT WAS NOT PROHIBITED IN SYSTEM.  RESPONDER LIFTED BOX AFTER CHECKING AND BOTTOM OF BOX FLAP CAME OPEN.  STYROFOAM INSERTS WERE BROKEN AND MIDDLE BOTTLE FELL OUT HIT THE METAL DOCK AND BROKE.  BOTTOM FLAP WAS NOT SECURELY CLOSED.
THE PACKAGE APPEARED TO HAVE FALLEN FROM THE LOAD AND STARTED TO LEAK.  THE PACKAGE CONTAIN 1 GLASS BOTTLE.
THE WET PACKAGE WAS OUTSIDE THE TRAILER IN A SPILL TUB.  ONE GLASS CONTAINER WAS BROKEN.  IT APPEARS THAT THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN DROPPED.
BOX WAS DROPPED CAUSING ONE OF THE INNER BOTTLES TO CRACK AND LEAK.
A LOOSE CAP ON ONE OF THE INNER BOTTLES CAUSED THE DAMAGE.
TRAILER WAS IN PROCESS OF BEING UNLOADED.  MANAGER INFORMED BY UNLOADER PACKAGE WAS LEAKING.  ONE OF THE INNER BOTTLES HAD CRACKED.  MAY HAVE BEEN DROPPED.
RESPONDED TO CALL AND FOUND LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILOR DOOR.  ONE OF THE INNER RECEPTACLES WAS CRACKED AND LEAKING.

THE PACKAGE WAS ON THE UNLOAD GRATING WAITING TO BE AUDITED BUT, BECAUSE OF ITS INTERIOR LEAK, THE PACKAGE WAS HELD OFF ON THE SIDE WAITING TO BE DISPOSED OF IN THE DMP.  THE PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT BACK TO PSC FOR FURTHER EVALUATION WHERE THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED TO BE A PIN-SIZE HOLE IN THE BLADDER THAT WAS HOLDING THE FLUID.  THERE WAS NO ABUSE TO THE EXTERIOR PACKAGING.  THE CAUSE OF THIS CAN BE ASSUMED TO BE MANUFACTURER ERROR.
BOX DROPPED FROM BELT, ONE INNER BOTTLE CRACKED AND LEAKED LIQUID.

Tank trailer was eastbound on I-84 when the driver moved to the right shoulder in an attempt to avoid a slow moving vehicle in the right lane. The tank trailer overturned on the right embankment, resulting in a release of approximately 784 gallons of waste acid material through a breach in the tank manway. The emergency response contractor righted the tanker and pumped off the remaining liquid to another tanker. Estimated duration of release was four hours. Impacted soil was removed and backfilled using clean soil after laboratory analysis confirmed cleanup was complete.  Personnel from the Oregon Department of Environmental Quality oversaw the response and cleanup activity.

column168: A BNSF inbound train/railcar inspection in the railyard revealed HOKX 8305 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) dripping liquid from the bottom of this tank car. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected HOKX 8305 and determined that residue product drips were emanating from a weep hole near the sump area. A receptacle was placed under HOKX 8305 and it was cordoned off in the railyard. BNSF contract responders plugged this weep hole. It was suspected that an internal liner breach resulted in residue product entering the weep hole area. A neutralizing mixture of soda ash and water was applied to residue product splashes on HOKX 8305 and an entrained adjacent railcar. All noted spillage that impacted the ballast area was also neutralized.  Afterwards, contract responders inserted the neutralizing solution inside HOKX 8305. The remaining neutralized content within HOKX 8305 was then vacuumed out. This material was placed in a poly tank which was later transported to the consignee for appropriate disposal. FRA movement approval FRA-09070284 was received for continued transportation back to the car owner consignee.   The side specification stencil on HOKX 8305 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2004 and next due in 2014.

column168: On June 28, 2009 at approximately 14:05 hrs., FRA Inspector Matsinger discovered UTLX 206100, a residue tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S, leaking from the vacuum relief device. The car was isolated and Hawkeye Growth was contacted thru Chemtrec (Report # 2009062800029). SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the O rings on the vacuum relief device had failed. SPSI personnel removed the defective device and sealed the car with a plug. The leak was secured and the car was held pending shipper disposition.    An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code: 458  NARRI: 5 (4+3+0) X (2+0) = 70

column168: YRC CITY DRIVER PICKED UP A TOTE FROM CUSTOMER'S DOCK THAT WAS LOADED WITH BENZENE.  AT THE DRIVER'S NEXT STOP HE NOTICED AN ODOR FROM THE TRAILER AND OPENED THE TRAILER TO CHECK ON HIS FREIGHT.  THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A TOTE TANK LEAKING AND CALLED HIS DISPATCHER WHO, IN TURN, CALLED THE YRC CHEMICAL HELPLINE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMETN WAS CALLED TO SECURE THE TRAILER UNTIL A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COULD ARRIVE.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED FOR EXPOSURE AS A PRECAUTION AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  MILSTEAD ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO HANDLE THE INCIDENT BY THE YRC CHEMICAL HELPLINE.  ON ARRIVAL MILSTEAD WAS ADVISED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT THEY HAD ALREADY MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TOLD MILSTEAD THAT THE TOTE WAS OVERFILLED AND THEY HAD DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT DRIPPING OUT OF THE PRESSURE RELEASE VALVE ON THE TOTE TANK.  THE HAZMAT TEAM BLED OFF 30 GALLONS OF BENZENE INTO A SALVAGE   RECOVERY DRUM AND DECONTAMINATED THE AFFECTED AREA OF THE SPILL.  THE SHIPPER REQUESTED THE TOTE AND SALVAGE DRUM OF PRODUCT BE RETURNED TO THEM.
column169: THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT'S FINDING OF THE TOTE BEING OVERFILLED CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO BE FORCED THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE FOR THEIR INVESTIGATION AND CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT FUTURE RELEASES.

column169: BETTER SECUREMENT OF CAP, BUNGS OR LIDS ON DRUMS. DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF PAILS, DRUMS, TOTES OR MISCELLANEOUS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. THE SEAMS ON THE PACKAGING MUST BE ABLE TO HOLD LIQUID WITHOUT LEAKING OUT. column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING DRUMS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  REMOVE AND AVOID OBSTRUCTIONS IN LANE OF TRAVEL TO PREVENT DAMAGE AND UNSAFE SITUATIONS.  PLACE CUSHIONING BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGE FREIGHT.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: At 06:00 on6/16/09, the Weatherford Buckhannon Manager was notified that an AT 0600 ON 6/16/2009, THE WEATHERFORD BUCKHANNON MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED THAT AN acid carrier in the yard was leaking 28% hydrochloric acid.  The leak was from a small (< 3") crack that had developed above a welded seam on the container.  Approximately 712 gallons of HCI was released onto the Weatherford Artificial Lift Systems (ALS) yard in Buckhannon, WV.  The National Response Center, the local fire department and the Upshur County Emergency Management Office were notified of the spill, and the West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection was notified.  The WVDEP oversaw the clean up activities conducted by Ryan Environmental on the behalf of Weatherford.  The release, limited to the Weatherford Property, was neutralized by the addition of soda ash and the affected soil was excavated and placed in lined roll off boxes pending disposal at an approved disposal facility. Confirmation samples were collected to verify that the clean up had been completed.  Based on the analytical results, no further additional action is required.
column169: Weatherford Artificial Lift Systems is conducting a Root Cause Analysis of the incident.  We are inspecting all of the tank containers at the facility.  We are also examining our internal requirements for inspecting and testing tank integrity and our acid loading practices.

column168: I received a phone call from FST Dispatcher Rob Horn 06/12/09, 7:50am. Rob stated that New Mexico Trooper called PST and said that our driver Joshua McAninch, traveling with a Westerh Refining Butane Load, from Bloomfield, NM with a destination of Western Refining El Paso, TX, was involved in a one vehicle rollover at approximately 7:17am Mountain Time; Location of accident; New Mexico, Interstate 25, Mile Marker #177. I then called New Mexico Sergeant Trooper Jason Green (575-835-0741) and New Mexico State Patrol Dispatch Marsha Roby (575-835-0741) to get details, Joshua was traveling Southbound an Interstate 25, when he apparently fell asleep, veered into the median, and overturned a loaded Butane Trailer (8666) & Tractor (87013). Trooper stated Joshua had been treated by EMS at the scene, and was transported to University of New Mexico Hospital. I then called PST Dispatch for help with finding another Driver with a pressurized bottle to possibly assist with unloading overturned Unit. FST HR Theresa Ford was notified and attempted calling (JNM Hospital to learn more of Joshua’s condition. FST driver Archie Carranza appeared to be the closest available unit, where he was currently unloading in Las Vegas, NM. I then called Sergeant Jason Green and told him we were arranging for our Unit to travel to Crash Site for offloading. He stated New Mexico HazMat had not been contacted, due to no release of Hazardous Material. Archic was running short of On Duty/Driving Hours, so I called for only available relief FST driver, Christine Lopez. Archic was directed to Crash site at 9:30am Central Time. FST Mechanic Ben Douglas was instructed to load proper unloading hoses, etc. and travel to Crash Site. Ben left at approximately 9:00am Central, I waited for Christine to arrive at Amarillo Yard, and we left at approximately 10:30 am Central, I had Mike MCDonald print last seven days of Joshua’s Driver Log. Arabic was first to arrive at scene at 12:30pm Central Time, and staged his tractor/trailer on North Bound side of 1-25 at nearest point of Crash Site. 1-25 Traffic by this time had been narrowed down to one lane on both North/South travel lanes. Approximately l0:32am Central Time; I persnally called New Mexico Department of Environmental Quality Frank R.odarte (505-428-2525), left message, and at approximately 10:37am Central Time, I also calld New Mexico DEQ Sandra Marlin (505-222-9547), left message, to report this incident, but never received a return call from either contacts. Made a call to Joshua’s wife 915-929-3698) at approximately 1:15pm, and left message for her to have Joshua call ne when possible, because it was necessary to complete a Post-Accident Alcohol Test Within eight hours of accident. Never received a return call. Christine lopez & I arrived at Crash Site at approximately 2:30pm Mountain Time. We hooked up to the disabled Trailêr #8666 (laying on its Right side), at approximately 3:30pm Central Time, and pumped as much as could onto mob

column168: When unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered three boxes that had been crushed by an unsecured piece of freight. As a result a couple of the inner containers were crushed as well and contributed to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container along with damaged containers.

While unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a metal can that was staged on a pallet slightly leaking from the bottom of the can by the seam. Apparently during transit the bottom of the can was rubbing against the wooden stringer board of the pallet and as a result this caused the seam to leak contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled materila was cleaned with sorbent material and placed into a recovery container along with the leaking can.
column169: Shippers should use dunnage on their pallets such as sheets of cardboard to help prevent these types of events from occurring.

column168: A Univar USA Inc. employee was driving a forklift and in the process of unloading an IBC from a Univar USA Inc. delivery box trailer spotted at the warehouse dock.  Due to the narrow dock door width, uneven level between trailer and dock floor and the IBC was at the rear of the trailer, the forklift had to approach the IBC at an angle.   The employee accidently punctured the IBC bottle with the forklift blade, near the IBC bottom.  This caused an 8 inch gash in the IBC bottle.   An estimated 138 gallons of product was released to the dock containment system and nearby catch basin.  No material was released to soil or water.  A response contractor was called in to vacuum up spilled material and to decontaminate surface areas.  The estimated release time was a few minutes.  Remedial actions were ongoing for six hours.
column169: Two corrective actions will be taken to prevent recurrence:  1. Forklift refresher training will be conducted.  2. The dock edge will be painted in a warning color to assist operators in identifying edge location.

column168: Our driver arrived at the consignee and parked on their scales outside of the plant facility.  The cargo tank was discovered to be leaking while parked there on their scales.  Plant personnel contacted Phillip Services who in turn sent two 70 barrel vaccuum trucks to the scales and removed the product from our cargo tank.      As the product was being unloaded, the leak increased in intensity and leaked 60 gallons of product onto the scales before all of the product was removed.  Plant personnel contained the product to their scales and cleaned up all of the spilled product.      The cargo tank was spotted in the plant until it stopped dripping then was cleaned and taken to Bulleye Tank in Houston, TX to locate the leak.  The leak originated from a pit in the barrel of the tank and has too many pits to be repaired so it was removed from service.  The cargo tank will now be sold for scrap.

column168: When driver got to the truck stop, he noticed drips from the bolts that connect the internal valve to the barrel of the cargo tank.  He had to move the trailer to the back of the lot and put a bucket under the drips.    There was a little pressure left on the cargo tank from loading.  He released the pressure and the drips slowed down.  Our spill response vendor, HMHTTC,  was called out to the scene.  The incident was reported to the state police who had said that the load needed to be transferred.  HMHTTC was able to determine that the bolts were loose.  They tightened the bolts to resolve the problem.  The trailer was pressurized then to make sure it wouldn't start leaking again.  It held pressure and the driver was released to continue on with the load.
column169: We are installing lock nuts on the cargo tanks to prevent them from loosening.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS.WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACE BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column169: SHIPPER MUST ENSURE ALL BOLTS AND SCREWS ARE TIGHT. VALVE, LIDS AND OTHER CLOSURES MUST BE SECURED AND TIGHTENED TO PREVENT EASY RELEASING THE LIQUID.THE DURABILITY OF A TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN AND CONTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS FROM SEAPING OUT. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. column168: AROUND 1045 OF THE REPORTED DAY, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE MOMENTARILY BECAME DISTRACTED WHILE TRANSITING A CURVE IN THE ROAD (E. BUTTE RD.) THE VEHICLE DRIFTED OUT OF ITS TRAFFIC LANE TO THE RIGHT SIDE.  THE VEHICLE WHEELS HIT THE ROADSIDE DITCH.  THE DRIVER OVER-CORRECTED AND LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE WHICH THEN ROLLED OVER.  CARGO STOWED ON THE FLAT-BED OF THE VEHICLE WAS EJECTED ON TO THT EROADWAY AND RIGHT-OF-WAY.DAMAGE TO BAGGED MATERIAL RESULTED FROM ABRASION OF THE PACKAGING STRIKING THE ROADWAY AND RIGHT-OF-WAY SURFACES. NO FUEL SPILL OCCURRED.                                                                                                                                                               THE VEHICLE CAME TO A REST AND THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO EXIT THE VEHICLE. THE DRIVER RECEIVED MINOR INJURIES AND WAS AMBULATORY AT THE SCENE.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CALL SUTTER COUNTY 911 WHO, IN TURN, DISPATCHED THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL AND SUTTER COUNTY FIRE DEPT.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR'S OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES AND THE U.S. COAST GUARD NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  CALIFORNIA OES ASSIGNED CONTROL NO. 09-4386 AND THE NRC ASSIGNED CASE NO. 908769 TO THE INCIDENT.                                                                  HELENA CHEMICAL CO. RESPONDED THROUGH ITS CLEANUP CONTRACTOR, CLEAN HARBORS, INC.  THE CONTRACTOR CREW ARRIVED ON-SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 AND BEGAN CONTAINING DAMAGED AND SPILLED CARGO.  CONTAINMENT WAS ACHIEVED BY APPROXIMATELY 2030.  ON THE FOLLOWING DAY, THE CONTRACTOR RETURNED TO REMOVE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  SUTTER COUNTY FIRE DEPT. MONITORED AND DIRECTED THE RESPONSE.  RESPONSE WAS TERMINATED AROUND 1200, JUNE 17, 2009.

column168: On June 18, 2009 a Veolia employee was loading a pallet of drums into a trailer using a electric pallet jack. One of the drums was punctured by a sharp metal edge of the trailer liner which was sticking out from the side wall of the trailer, located approximately 7 inches off of the trailer floor.  Approximately 3 gallons of the material had leaked onto the trailer floor.  The leaking drum was overpacked into a 95-gallon drum. The material that had leaked onto the floor of the trailer was cleaned up with speedi-dry and absorbant pads. The cleanup materials were placed into a 30-gallon drum for disposal.
column169: The cause of the spill was due to a faulty trailer liner.  The liner was immediately repaired after this incident occured.  As a result of this incident, trailer liners are inspected daily at the Latham, NY  intransit facility. Training has been implemented to help prevent recurrences of this type of incident.

column169: DRIVER WAS ISSUED APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINARY ACTION.  PACKAGINGS CONTAINING CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND RADIOACTIVE MATERIALS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE LEAVING ORIGIN! ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE BLOCKED AND BRACED TO PREVENT MOVEMENT AND FALLING OVER WHILE UNIT IS MOVING.  USE LOAD LOCK BARS, STRAPS AND MTY PALLETS TO ENSURE LOAD IS SAFE AND SECURE BEFORE MOVING.  PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND/ OR DUNNAGE.  USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF!  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RETRAINING IN HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGE STATING, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER TO MAKE SURE LIDS ON DRUMS ARE SECURED.

Re: RNC Report #909881; Hazardous Materials Incident   Dear Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety Administration,   This letter is in regards to transportation incident that occurred on June 24,2009 with our employee, Mr. John Tagliamburis, who drives truck unit number 289. On that day at 9:05 a.m. Mr. Tagliamburis was in Cheyenne, Wyoming. He called and spoke to me. He stated that he had conducted a walk around inspection and noticed approximately half a gallon of catalyst under the second bin on the right side. I asked Mr. Tagliamburis if any substance was on the ground. He replied, “No, it’s under the bin opening”.   After my conversation with Mr. Tagliamburis I called ASTE and spoke to Joyce. I infonned Joyce that a bin was showing some leakage but was not leaking while it was parked. Joyce informed me that she would call Wes at Conoco Phillips in Billings, Montana, which is where the load was generated. Joyce called me back shortly thereafter and stated that she had spoke to Wes and he ask if the leakage was enough to be reported. It was determined by Joyce and I, based on Mr. Tagliamburis’ description of the amount of the leakage, that the leakage amounted to less than a pound. I instructed Mr.   Tagliamburis to safely clean the area and put the leakage in a steel bucket with a lid. I also instructed him to check the door to make sure that it was completely closed with locks in place. John stated that he could not close the door anymore and couldn’t see the locks. It was then decided that since it was not showing any leakage while stopped, Mr. Tagliamburis could continue on. I repeatedly attempted to call Mr. Tagliamburis but was unable to reach him due to a lack of cell phone signal in that region.   The next morning, June 25th, 2009,1 called Mr. Tagliamburis. He reported that while enroute he had cleaned up a total of 4 ‘/2 gallons of leakage into the steel bucket. It was then decided that we would make a second door against the lip of the opening of the door. I then called Joyce at ASH. and informed her on the status of the load and how we had put a second door on the bin to eliminate the loss and that there might be a gallon that was between the bins that we could not get until the bins were removed or picked up. I then called the owner of Pride Transportation, Inc., Jim Kilgore, and asked him if he wanted us to continue with the load and plan on the remaining leakage to be cleaned between the bins upon delivery. Mr. Kilgore instructed me to instruct Mr. Tagliamburis to continue with his planned delivery.   Mr. Tagliamburis called me the next morning at his delivery destination, Porocel Catalyst Recovery. He told me that everything was fine with the load, Porocel Catalyst   Recovery signed the bills and cleaned the leakage on the floor. Mr. Tagliamburis told me to call and speak to Sean at Porocel. I asked Mr. Tagliamburis if anything was written by Porocel on lines 18 and 1 8a showing a discrepancy. Mr. Tagliamburis stated there was

column168: A CHLORINE TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS LOADED AT THE CENTRAL PLANT FOR SHIPMENT TO THE WEST PLANT.  AFTER PULLING ONTO US HIGHWAY 15 ENTRANCE, THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE APPARENTLY OPENED FOR 1/2 SECOND RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 6.18 POUNDS OF CHLORINE VAPOR.  SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AUTOMATICALLY RE-CLOSED.  A MOTORIST DRIVING ALONG HWY 15 SMELLED THE VAPOR, AND PULLED HIS TRUCK INTO CHEMTURA'S DRIVE AND PARKING AREA.  MOTORIST EXISTED HIS TRUCK.  CHEMTURA EMPLOYEED OBSERVED THAT MOTORIST WAS COUGHING AND REQUESTED AN AMBULANCE.  PLANT MEDICAL RESPONDERS WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  A PLANT EMPLOYEE NOTICED A CHLORINE ODOR ON THE HIGHWAY AND STOPPED THE DRIVER/TRUCK WITH 1/2 MILE OF THE PLANT/ HIGHWAY ENTRANCE.  BOTH DRIVER AND PLANT EMPLOYEE INSPECTED THE TRUCK/TRAILER AND FOUND NO LEAKAGE.  ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS FOUND THAT TANK BAFFLE DESIGN ALLOWED EXCESSIVE LOAD SHIFTING OF THE CHLORINE LIQUID, CAUSING HYDAULIC LIFTING OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  TRAILER WAS SUCCESSFULLY UNLOADED WITH NO FURTHER RELEASES.  CORRECTIVE ACTION TO REPLACE MANUFACTURER'S BAFFLE WITH FULL-SIZED BAFFLE COMPLETE.

column168: 10:35AM CALL FROM JOSE AGUIRE (194/223) COMES IN REPORTING OF COLLISON ACCIDENT ON I-10 EASTBOUND 5 MILES NORTH OR PICACHO PEAK, MILEMARKER 214.1.  I ASKED JOSE AGUIRE IF HE WAS OK, HE SAID YES, I ASKED IF RAMON AGUIRRE WAS OK, HE SAID YES.  JOSE AGUIRE SAID THE PERSON FROM THE OTHER VEHICLE DID NOT SURVIVE FROM IMPACTING TANKER 223.  I ASKED IF EMERGENCY RESPONDERS HAVE ARRIVED, JOSE AGUIRRE SAID YES.  ASKED ABOUT THE COLLISION, JOS AGUIRRE REPORTED THAT THE TANKER'S AXLE NO. 4 AND 5 HAVE BEEN SEPARTED FROM TANKER, TANKER 223 NO LONGER ABLE TO MOVE, NEED "LOW-BOY" TO HAUL TANKER OFF HIGHWAY.  10:45AM NOTIFIED OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR OSCAR GARDEA OF INCIDENT, INSTRUCTED TO HEAD OUT TO SCENE OF ACCIDENT.  11:10AM ENTERED I-19 AT MARIPOSAA RD, HEADING NORTH TOWARDS PICACHO.  11:15AM RECEIVED CALL FROM "CHAD" OF CONOCO IN HOUSTON, TX REGARDING PRODUCT, DESTINATION, CONSIGNESS, AND BOL NUMBER.  UNABLE TO RECORD HIS CALL BACK NUMBER BECAUSE I WAS DRIVING AT THE TIME.  11:25AM VIA JOSE AGUIRE'S PERSONAL CELL-PHONE, SPOKE WITH DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY OFFICER FROM SCENE OF ACCIDENT.  DPS WANTS PRODUCT IN TANKER 223 TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TANKER BEFORE REMOVING TANKER 223 FROM SCENE.  TOLD DPS OFFICER THAT CALIFORNIA GAS TRANSPORT WILL CONTACT BARNETT'S FOR RECOVERY EFFORTS.  11:35AM CONTACTED BARNETT'S IN TUCSON, AZ AND SPOKE WITH TY WILDMAN.  REQUESTED TANKER TO TRANSFER OUR PRODUCT INTO THEIR TANKER, ALSO REQUESTED A "LOW-BOY" FOR TANKER 223.  12:20PM CONTACTED MASSEY TRUCK AND TANK REPAIR IN PHOENIX, AZ SPOKE WITH TONY ABOUT SITUATION.  AGREED TO RECEIVED TANKER 223.  1:00PM ARRIVED TO SCENE OF ACCIDENT AT MILEMARKER 214.  DPS OFFICER STATED THAT OUR DRIVERS ARE OK, THAT A VEHICLE INSPECTION WAS CONDUCTED ON UNIT 194/223 AND PASSED INSPECTION.  DPS OFFICER ALSO SAID THAT AS FAR AS CALIFORNIA GAS TRANSPORT IS INVOLVED, WE ARE CLEAR.  2:15PM RECOVERY TEAM FROM BARNETT'S ARRIVE TO SCENE OF ACCIDENT.  3:00PM BARNETT'S BEGAN WORK ON HOOKING UP HOSES TO TANKER 223 TO A TANKER OF THEIRS TO TRANSFER PROPANE.  3:50PM AFTER STRUGGLING TO GET INTERNAL VALVE ON TANKER 223 TO OPEN, THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM TANKER 223 TO BARNETT'S TANKER INITIATED.  5:00PM BARNETT'S TANKER FILLED TO 70% (WITH WATER CAPACITY OF 11,500GLNS) AND UNHOOKED HOSES.  BARNETT'S RECOVERY TEAM BEGAN STRAPPING TANKER 223 TO LIFT FROM PAVEMENT.  6:00PM TANKER 223 SECURED ON BARNETT'D LOW-BOY.  TANKER 223 STILL CONTAINS ABOUT 4% OF PRODUCT.  TRACTOR 194 NOT DAMAGED AND IN OPERATING CONDITION.  HAUL TANKER 223 TO SAFE LOCATION FOR COMPLETION OF TRANSFERRING PRODUCT.  6:31PM ARRIVED TO OPEN SPORT TO FINISH TRANSFERRING PRODUCT FROM TANKER 223 TO BARNETT'S TANKER.  RAMON AND JOSE AGUIRRE FOLLOWED TO LOCATION IN TRACTOR NO. 194.  7:15PM TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM TANKER 223 BARNETT'S TANKER COMPLETED.  BARNETT'T TANKER READS AT 75% FULL.  7:30PM LEAVE PICACHO FOR TUCSON, AZ.  RAMON AND JOSE AGUIRRE FOLLOWED ME TO TUCSON IN TRACTOR NO. 194.  8:00PM WE ARRIVED TO TUSCON, AZ AND BEGIN DRIVING TOW

column168: Our driver, Kent Cofield, was traveling north on Oklahoma state highway 183 with 187 barrels of crude oil loaded on a tractor/tank trailer. As he was attempting to make a left turn onto the on ramp of I-40 west, his rate of speed caused the transport to overturn onto it's right side. The impact caused the tractor frame to puncture the shell of the cargo tank trailer. This resulted in the release of product that ignited. Our driver was killed in the accident and the tractor/trailer was completely destroyed by the fire. We picked up 107 barrels of crude oil and 80 barrels was lost in the fire.
column169: Training was enhanced with all drivers during safety meetings to emphasize proper driving techniques for loaded transports.

column168: At 09:58 on 11 June, 2009, Bill Walters accompanied passenger SCOTT HICKOFF (Quadco employee)  into the secure baggage area of the NAC/SSA terminal so Mr. Hickoff could retrieve his jacket from his checked bag [Badami Tag: 00-38-99]. When Mr. Hickoff opened his bag, which had just come off Shared Services flight 131 from Anchorage, Bill Walters saw an aerosol spray can in his bag.  Bill Walters asked Mr. Hickoff what the aerosol was, and he showed it to me. I saw that it was a flammable aerosol.      Bill Walters asked Mr Hickoff if he declared the hazmat in Anchorage when he checked in for flight 131. He said that he “Did Not, Bill Walters didn’t know it was in there, it was for a home project”.     Bill Walters saw that the can was a 340 gram aerosol of “Clear Transparent Shellac” [Mfg: Zinsser Company, Product code  00408]. The can had been partially crushed in flight, but does not appear to have been ruptured. The can is clearly marked “Extreme Danger – Very Flammable”.      Aerosol Shellac is a hazardous material, classified as: AEROSOLS, UN 1950  Class 2.1   (Not to exceed 1 Liter) Properly packaged, labeled, and documented it is shippable as a hazardous material, but it is prohibited in passenger checked or carry on baggage.     Passenger Information:    Scott E. Hickoff Employer:  Quadco  3705 Arctic Blvd, # 1076  Anchorage, Ak  99503  Cell phone: 862-571-5790  DOB: 1-31-54
column169: Bill Walters explained to Mr HICKOFF that it was illegal  to transport that product in his checked or hand carry baggage  (49 CFR 175.3) .  Bill Walters asked him if he wanted me to ship it to Badami (as a hazardous material), but he said that he did not need it at Badami, and he gave the can to me. He said that he did not know it was in his bag. Bill Walters provided a receipt for the Shellac to Mr. Hickoff.

column168: Flight 444 arrived from AUS at approximately 0926 on the 06/20/2009.  Upon offloading the middle belly of the aircraft it was found that one piece of US MAIL was leaking.     The USPS was not immediately available to respond to the incident to open the mail sack.  The aircraft was to turn flight 444 outbound to BOS.  The spill resulted in the need to change equipment.      The mail sack was eventually opened where it was revealed that this box was clearly marked "liquid" on the outside of the box and a customs declaration for Canada was filled out and indicated "insecticide".  The box was placed inside an orange mail sack, therefore American Airlines was not aware of the contents being tendered by the USPS.    Upon opening of the mail sack there were three items found packaged in the box.  The item that had leaked was a one gallon container of Tengard SFR One Shot Insecticide.  Approximately 1 pint of the liquid had spilled.  MSDS of the product indicates that it is not regulated as per 173.150(f) when shipped by highway in non-bulk containers.  However, when shipped via air it should be transported under UN1993, Flammable liquid, n.o.s (hydrocarbon), hazard class 3, PGIII.      There were two other materials inside the box that did not leak.  One was Prentox ExciteR, transport information states, NA1993, Combustible liquid, n.o.s. (Petroleum Naptha), PGIII, RQ (Pyrethrins).  The last material inside the package was a package of 20 of Summit Bti Briquets (mosquito dunks).  This material does not indicate to be regulated for transport.    The material was cleaned up by Eagle Construction and Environmental Services.      Due to the slow response of the USPS, the clean up for this event was not concluded until approximately 1500, resulting in the aircraft being out of service for approximately 5 1/2 hours.
column169: All triggers were on the box at time of tender from customer to the USPS.  The box was labeled "liquid" and the customs release was attached to the box with contents indicating "insecticide".  Perhaps better training for personnel to catch "triggers" to ask questions on the items being shipped, and better education to the customer who was shipping the insecticides.  Had this shipment been properly declared the incident could have been prevented.
